https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/how-to-set-up-python-2-7-6-and-3-3-3-on-centos-6-4

wget http://www.python.org/ftp/python/2.7.6/Python-2.7.6.tar.xz
wget http://www.python.org/ftp/python/3.3.3/Python-3.3.3.tar.xz
 yum install xz-libs
# Let's decode (-d) the XZ encoded tar archive:
xz -d Python-2.7.6.tar.xz


# Now we can perform the extraction:
tar -xvf Python-2.7.6.tar
Example for version 3.3.3:

xz -d Python-3.3.3.tar.xz
tar -xvf Python-3.3.3.tar
cd Python-2.7.6
./configure --prefix=/pkg/python/2.7.10
make
make install 

or  Normally, one would use “make install”; however, in order not to override system defaults - replacing the Python already used by the system - we will use make altinstall. 
make && make altinstall 

export PATH="/okg/python/2.7.10/bin:$PATH"


Setting Up Common Python Tools pip and virtualenv
Having installed Python, we can now finalize completing the basics for application production and deployment. For this, we will set up two of the most commonly used tools: pip package manager and virtualenv environment manager.


Before installing pip, we need to get its only external dependency - setuptools.


wget --no-check-certificate https://pypi.python.org/packages/source/s/setuptools/setuptools-17.0.tar.gz#md5=fd15d24ed1e4c95e56d8c6e812f3a84f

# Extract the files from the archive:
tar -xvf setuptools-1.4.2.tar.gz

# Enter the extracted directory:
cd setuptools-1.4.2

# Install setuptools using the Python we've installed (2.7.6)
python2.7 setup.py install

now install pip use curl:

curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/pypa/pip/master/contrib/get-pip.py | python2.7 -


now pip is installed !!!


now install the virtualenv by pip 

pip install virtualenv



easy_install --install-dir=/pkg/python-modules/lib/python2.7/site-packages 'libgtk'
